<h2>Google Business Profile for Locksmiths</h2>
<p>Your <a href="/blog/optimize-google-business-profile/">Google Business Profile</a> is the single most important local SEO asset for a locksmith business. It determines whether you show up in the map pack, which captures 42% of clicks for local searches.</p>
<h3>Setting Up Your Profile the Right Way</h3>
<p>Google has cracked down hard on locksmith GBP listings. The platform removed over 10,000 fake locksmith listings in a single sweep and <a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/google-maps-fake-listings-lawsuit-scams/">sued an alleged network of scammers</a> operating fake local listings. Legitimate locksmiths must set up their profiles with extra care.</p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Use your real, legal business name (no keyword stuffing in the name)</li>
<li>[ ] Verify with a physical address where you receive mail</li>
<li>[ ] Select "Locksmith" as your primary category</li>
<li>[ ] Add secondary categories: "Emergency Locksmith Service," "Lock Store," "Security System Installer"</li>
<li>[ ] Upload your ALOA membership certificate or state license</li>
</ul>
<h3>Optimizing Every Field</h3>
<p><strong>Business description:</strong> Write 750 characters that include your primary services (emergency lockout, lock rekey, deadbolt installation, transponder key programming), service area, and operating hours. Mention "licensed and insured" and "bonded" if applicable.</p>
<p><strong>Services:</strong> List every service you offer with descriptions. Google uses this data for matching searches.</p>
