<h2>Technical SEO for Locksmith Websites</h2>
<p>A locksmith website that loads slowly on mobile will lose emergency customers. Someone locked out of their car at midnight will not wait 5 seconds for your page to load. <a href="/glossary/technical-seo/">Technical SEO</a> ensures your site performs when it matters most.</p>
<h3>Mobile Speed Is Non-Negotiable</h3>
<p>Over 56% of home service searches happen on mobile devices. For emergency locksmith searches, that number is likely above 80%. Your site must load in under 2.5 seconds on a 4G connection.</p>
<p>Check your <a href="/blog/improve-core-web-vitals/">Core Web Vitals</a>:</p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Largest Contentful Paint (LCP) under 2.5 seconds</li>
<li>[ ] Interaction to Next Paint (INP) under 200 milliseconds</li>
<li>[ ] Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS) under 0.1</li>
</ul>
<h3>Click-to-Call on Every Page</h3>
<p>Every page needs a prominent click-to-call button. Place your phone number in the header, in the hero section, and in the footer. Use <code>tel:</code> links so mobile users can tap to call. Locksmiths sell response time. Make it effortless to reach you.</p>
<h3>Schema Markup for Locksmiths</h3>
<p><a href="/glossary/schema-markup/">Schema markup</a> helps Google understand your business. Use a <a href="/tools/schema-markup-generator/">schema markup generator</a> to create structured data.</p>
<p>Essential schema types:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>LocalBusiness</strong> (or Locksmith). Name, address, phone, hours, service area</li>
<li><strong>Service</strong>. For each service page</li>
<li><strong>FAQ</strong>. For FAQ pages and blog posts</li>
<li><strong>Review</strong>. Aggregate ratings from Google reviews</li>
</ul>
<h3>XML Sitemap and Site Security</h3>
<p>Create an <a href="/blog/create-xml-sitemap/">XML sitemap</a> and submit it through <a href="/blog/google-search-console-guide/">Google Search Console</a>. Configure your <a href="/blog/optimize-robots-txt/">robots.txt</a> correctly. Run HTTPS on every page. A "Not Secure" warning in the browser will scare away customers who are about to share their home address with a stranger.</p>
